Twitter US Airline Sentiment¶

Description¶

Background and Context:

Twitter possesses 330 million monthly active users, which allows businesses to reach a broad population and connect with customers without intermediaries. On the other hand, there’s so much information that it’s difficult for brands to quickly detect negative social mentions that could harm their business.

That's why sentiment analysis/classification, which involves monitoring emotions in conversations on social media platforms, has become a key strategy in social media marketing.

Listening to how customers feel about the product/service on Twitter allows companies to understand their audience, keep on top of what’s being said about their brand and their competitors, and discover new trends in the industry.

Data Description:

A sentiment analysis job about the problems of each major U.S. airline. Twitter data was scraped from February of 2015 and contributors were asked to first classify positive, negative, and neutral tweets, followed by categorizing negative reasons (such as "late flight" or "rude service").

Dataset:

The dataset has the following columns:

tweet_id
airline_sentiment
airline_sentiment_confidence
negativereason
negativereason_confidence
airline
airline_sentiment_gold
name
negativereason_gold retweet_count text tweet_coord tweet_created tweet_location user_timezone

Opinion: I am neutral when it comes to airlines, I fly often between states and they are all pretty much the same.

Unfortunately the dataset features are not very detailed to explain what they are and how the info was obtained so assumptions will be made on the features (that they are self explanatory) and the data contained in them.

# Function to plot the sentiment of the dataframe with the sentiment
def plotTweetSentiment(df, sentiment):
  # DataFrame created for visual
  plotTweetSenti = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Counts', 'Airlines'] )

  # get a roster of the different airlines
  airlines_roster = df['airline'].unique()
  # get the sentiment into its own list
  sentiment = df[df['airline_sentiment']==sentiment]

  # Cycle through the airlines and count the sentiments  then add to table
  for i in range(0,airlines_roster.size):
    # count the sentiments
    tally = sentiment[sentiment['airline'] == airlines_roster[i]].count()['airline_sentiment']
    # 'insert' count and airline into table the print it
    plotTweetSenti.loc[i] = [tally, airlines_roster[i]]
    print (tally," ",airlines_roster[i])

  # return barplot with dataframe created & inserted/appended to
  return sns.barplot(data=plotTweetSenti , x='Airlines', y='Counts')

def show_wordcloud(Positive_sent, title):
    text = ' '.join(Positive_sent['text'].astype(str).tolist())
    stopwords = set(wordcloud.STOPWORDS)
    
    fig_wordcloud = wordcloud.WordCloud(stopwords=stopwords,background_color='white',
                    colormap='viridis', width=800, height=600).generate(text)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(14,11), frameon=True)
    plt.imshow(fig_wordcloud)  
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.title(title, fontsize=30)
    plt.show()

HTML tag removal¶

In [24]:
# Function to remove html tags & hypertext transfer protocol text (http)
def remove_html_https(text):
  # Removes all HTML through BeautifulSoup
  text = BeautifulSoup(text, "html.parser") # Removing HTML tags
  # removes https from string until the next white-space 
  text = re.sub(r"http\S+", "", text.get_text())

  # returns cleaned text
  return text

Special Characters & Punctuations Removal¶

In [29]:
def remove_non_ascii(words):
  """Remove non-ASCII characters from list of TOKENIZED words"""
  new_words = []
  for word in words:
    # standardizes the characters: non-accented, no tildas or unique characters outside of English
    new_word = unicodedata.normalize('NFKD', word).encode('ascii', 'ignore').decode('utf-8', 'ignore')
    new_words.append(new_word)
  return new_words
tweet_data_TEXT_SENTIMENT['text'] = tweet_data_TEXT_SENTIMENT['text'].apply(lambda i: remove_non_ascii(i))

# Removes all punctions
def remove_punctuation(words):
  """Remove punctuation from list of TOKENIZED words"""
  new_words = []
  for word in words:
    new_word = re.sub(r'[^\w\s]', ' ', word)
    if new_word != '':
      # Append processed words to new list, if not NULL aka ''. Still keeps the white-spaces.
      new_words.append(new_word)
  return new_words
tweet_data_TEXT_SENTIMENT['text'] = tweet_data_TEXT_SENTIMENT['text'].apply(lambda i: remove_punctuation(i))

def to_lowercase(words):
  """Convert all characters to lowercase from list of TOKENIZED words"""
  new_words = []
  # Cycle through text & convert to lowercase
  
  # cycles through text and changes each character to lowercase then adds to the list
  for word in words:
    new_word = word.lower()
    new_words.append(new_word)
  return new_words

def remove_stopwords(words):
  """Remove stop words from list of TOKENIZED words"""
  new_words = []
  # if the word isn't in the stop list, add it to our list
  # cycle through the text
  for word in words:
    if word not in stopwords:
      new_words.append(word)
  return new_words

Fit, tune (optimize the parameter to improve the accuracy) & evaluate the model using both types of vectorization. Print the top 40 features and plot their word cloud using both types of vectorization.¶

In [47]:
# Finding optimal base learners number
base_ln = [x for x in range(1, 40)]
base_ln

# K-Fold Cross - validation .
cv_scores = []
for b in base_ln:
    clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators = b)
    scores = cross_val_score(clf, CV_X_train, CV_y_train, cv = 5, scoring = 'accuracy')
    cv_scores.append(scores.mean())

# plotting the error as k increases
#error corresponds to each number of estimator
error = [1 - x for x in cv_scores]
#Selection of optimal number of n_estimator corresponds to minimum error.
optimal_learners = base_ln[error.index(min(error))]
#Plot between each number of estimator and misclassification error
plt.plot(base_ln, error)  
xy = (optimal_learners, min(error))
plt.annotate('(%s, %s)' % xy, xy = xy, textcoords='data')
plt.xlabel("Number of base learners")
plt.ylabel("Misclassification Error")
plt.show()

Observations & Insights: The optimal amount seems to be somewhere around 13 for CountVector.

Summarize your understanding of the application of Various Pre-processing and Vectorization and the performance of your model on this dataset¶

While the data captured was unstructured as we would expect from a service like Twitter, we can preprocess our data with a four-phase process to be able to prep it for Vectorization.

The first is to break down the simple elements available to us with BeautifulSoup & RegEx packages such as HTML tags, HTTPS:// weblinks, numbers. We can use an additional package called contractions to expand out works like don’t, haven’t to do not, have not.

The second phase is to ‘tokenize’ our text into various strings for further processing. This is important because this objectifies each word as a unique instance to be able to standardize ASCII, remove punctuation, convert to lowercase and finally, remove stop words that add no value to meaning. This could not be done if each word was not a unique element instead of a continuous string.

The third phase is to Lemmatize the words to ensure the words are broken down even more to remote grammar and just keep the essence or root of each word.

The final process is to stitch the unique elements into continuous strings again and then replace the content of where it previously was.

Once the four phases are complete, we can move onto Vectorization. As for performance, CountVectorizer and TFIDFVectorizer did not have much of an impact on accuracy of the Random Forest. This may be a result of the data sample provided.
